# Toshi config — copy this to .env and fill only what you want. Your real .env is gitignored, so keys
# stay local (that was a real hole once — .env wasn't ignored). Toshi runs fine with NONE of these set:
# the mascot floats and answers in an honest "demo mode". Set a provider key to unlock chat + voice.

# ── Brain (chat + the spoken text). Pick ONE provider key. OpenRouter is the easy default (free models
#    exist; the built-in default is a free llama-3.3-70b). Get one at openrouter.ai/keys.
#    Step-by-step: docs/openrouter-key.md  (where to put the key on Win / mac / Linux, how to verify, free models, troubleshooting).
OPENROUTER_API_KEY=
# …or use another provider instead of OpenRouter:
# XAI_API_KEY=
# GROQ_API_KEY=
# OPENAI_API_KEY=
# …or a fully custom OpenAI-compatible endpoint:
# TOSHI_API_URL=
# TOSHI_API_KEY=
# TOSHI_API_MODEL=
#
# Prefer the CLI over editing this file:  toshi model minimax/minimax-m3   (picks the brain model)
# Turn ALL LLM off (no chat, no spoken text):  TOSHI_LLM=off

# ── Voice (audio TTS — open-source, local). Default is the OS Web Speech voice (0 download).
#    Upgrade to the credible local voice:  toshi voice kokoro   ·   see all:  toshi voice --list
# TOSHI_TTS=off        # mute Toshi (text bubbles still work)

# ── Advanced (rarely needed)
# TOSHI_PORT=4820           # the brain's HTTP port the panel talks to
# CODEBASE_MEMORY_BIN=      # explicit path to codebase-memory-mcp if it isn't auto-found
# TOSHI_AUTOINDEX=off       # don't auto-index a repo the first time Toshi connects to it
